\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The canteen dilemma: Higher-order social reasoning in a coordination game
 with imperfect information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Thomas Schrum Nicolet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset line
LatexCommand rule
offset "0.5ex"
width "100col%"
height "1pt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
thispagestyle{empty}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Social interaction often depends on the ability to correctly attribute mental
 states to others.
 This capacity is traditionally referred to as theory of mind and is a fundament
al mechanic behind social dynamics.
 The canteen dilemma is a game aimed at testing how this ability is drawn
 upon in coordination problems without common knowledge.
 Findings
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://github.com/thomasnicolet/canteen-dilemma-thesis
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the Python code which makes up the data analysis of the experiment.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from the experiment suggest that adults are indeed limited to second-order
 reasoning at most.
 Most importantly, the results suggest that the higher-order beliefs of
 participants exist in various degrees not encapsulated by traditional descripti
ons of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 theory of mind.
 The present paper also introduce research on social cognition and discuss
 certain conceptual issues within the field as give a case example of the
 importance of social cognition.
\end_layout

